PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) â€” A Rhode Island man who along with an accomplice fraudulently sought hundreds of thousands of dollars in coronavirus pandemic relief loans intended for struggling small businesses avoided prison and was sentenced Wednesday to three years of probation.David Andrew Butziger, 53, of Warwick, must spend the first six months of his sentence in home confinement and was also ordered to pay a $5,000 fine, according to a statement from the office of U.S. Attorney for Rhode Island, Zachary Cunha.Butziger and his accomplice, David Staveley, 54, of Andover, Massachusetts, sought to defraud the Paycheck Protection Program by seeking more than $500,000 in forgivable loans by claiming to have dozens of employees at three restaurants and a communications company, when, in fact, there were no employees at any of them.They were the first people in the country accused of fraudulently seeking PPP loans when they were first charged in May 2020, according to prosecutors.Butziger pleaded guilty in October 2020 to conspiracy to commit bank fraud.Staveley, who faked his own death after his initial arrest and went on the run for several months before he was caught, pleaded guilty last May and was sentenced in October to nearly five years in prison.